metadata.name: ecologías - A #725
metadata.description:
ecologías - A

lines are a metaphor for the communication all species engage in. We as humans have a need to leave traces - stories - that others can read and learn from. What will be the traces machines want to leave? This piece employs sinusoidal signals drawn with lines as a simple metaphor for every trace and every language, for every message and every communication.

ecologías-A is an entity that is part of a broader ecology. Released on occasion of the show "Unbound - Ecology in the Age of Machines" at Unit London. The data generated by this entity is read by a different piece minted on Ethereum, creating a link between Tezos and Ethereum, a metaphor for an ecology of blockchains.

it shares a common element with two other works released on fxhash: ecologías B and ecologías C, all of them contributing data to aforementioned pieces.

read more at https://www.iillucid.com/ecologias

15% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro
CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/

Built on p5.js, glsl

append &pd=N (N a number) to the URL in live view to increase/decrease resolution
press s to save current image in current resolution
press z,x,g,b,n followed by +/- to increase/decrease, respectively, brightness, contrast, gamma, blur, noise

metadata.name: Handachak #110
metadata.description:
I have always been looking for solutions that can connect different visual elements in such a way as to create an integrated system and structure and each part of the work plays its own role in this system.
Another point is that always attributing physical characteristics to abstract forms creates aesthetic qualities. From a general point of view, one of these features is perspective, and in this project we see a type of perspective in an abstract and geometric structure.
"Handachak" means "Geometry" in ancient Persian.

metadata.name: Tangentum #208
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: the endless dance #50
metadata.description:
“We thought of life by analogy with a journey, a pilgrimage, which had a serious purpose at the end, and the thing was to get to that end, success or whatever it is, maybe heaven after you’re dead. But we missed the point the whole way along. It was a musical thing and you were supposed to sing or to dance while the music was being played.” ― Alan Watts

mousedown: overdraw

metadata.name: GuageTiles #10
metadata.description:
An interactive tiled pattern is generated with the fxhash which determines two features at random.

"groundsState" value determines a base configuration and is sampled uniformly at random in the range 0 to 1.

"spectralGap" determines the color of the pattern and comes in three types::
'low' (30%) is monochrome
'mid' (60%) is small hue range
'high' (10%) is a large hue range

*click/touch & hold/move* the canvas to charge the pattern and change the flux mode of the tiles.
*release* the canvas and the pattern decays back to its "groundState" value.

metadata.name: ThetaStar #17
metadata.description:
A "ThetaStar" is generated through an Iterated Function System determined by the fxhash with one main feature 'Theta' corresponding to an angle value in radians sampled uniformly at random in the range 2.5 < Theta < 3.0.

**Click / Touch** the canvas to reset and watch the "ThetaStar" gradually radiate in full spectrum.
The visually daring may **Rapidly Click / Touch** for an enhanced strobe like effect.

metadata.name: Origins Unknown #342
metadata.description:
An exploration of layers shapes and colors resulting in "Origins Unknown".

**Colors**
Thousands of color combos derived from 6 palettes including day/night variations.

**Horizons**
Horizon color, line count, shape, angle, position.

**Planets**
Planet color/gradient, count, size, position.

**Structures**
Structure color/gradient, count, density, position.

metadata.name: 70s Tapestry #37
metadata.description:
70s Tapestry is a tribute to the fine art work of embroiderers, and the 70s design.

Variations include :

- 10 Color Palettes
- Dark or Light background
- A reversed color mode
- 1 or 2 palettes used
- 4 types of framing, including a randomized one
- 3 types of embroidery tile type distribution
- and some special rare traits
